			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="font-weight: bold">How to Solo Neh`Ashir </span>
<br />

<br />
I just recently got my torch from Neh`Ashir I thought that I would consolidate the information I found from various sources combined with my experience. I’ve broken the process into four phases (it’s not really that complicated, though). The phases are: 1) getting to and clearing the area, 2) targeting the desired Black Reaver, 3) pulling the Black Reaver, 4) killing the Black Reavers/Neh`Ashir. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Notes: </span>
<br />
I did this solo as a 65th level Mage. I would guess that this could be done solo beginning at 61, possibly a bit lower if the Mage has their epic. I recommend 61 because I think that Ward of Xegony (the 61st level pet) is a huge advantage here. With two, or a small group, this can probably be done down to the low 50’s, but clearing and minimizing adds (easy at 65) will become a problem in itself at these lower levels.  I later did this with a group with characters as low as 49th and the agro increase was very significant.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Setup: </span>
<br />
I used the 61st level pet, Ward of Xegony. I gave it the Muzzle of Mardu, the Girdle of Magi`Kot and two weapons (I used the Fists). I also gave it a set of summoned armor (which does make a difference when solo) and a set of summoned focus items (couldn’t hurt). I kept BO5 and a DS on the pet at all times. 
<br />

<br />
I buffed myself; MR gear is great if you have it. I would also recommend getting C5 if possible. If not, get C3 as a minimum. 
<br />

<br />
I memmed My best DD (Sun Vortex), a low-level bolt (Scars of Sigil), debuffing (Mala and Malosini), a DS (Flameshield of Ro), a pet heal (Planar Renewal) and Annul Magic. Actually, you won’t need annul until Neh`Ashir pops and you won’t need the debuffing until you pull the Black Reavers, so you can substitute other spells before then. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Getting There: </span>
<br />
First, make sure you know where you’re going. The EQ Atlas maps (here in an earlier post) are great. As was described in those earlier posts, you need to fight your way into the far Northwest corner of the zone (loc 250, 350). This should be easy. If you can’t do this part, forget about the Reavers. Once there, continue clearing the corridor eastward to the dead end. You’ll need to keep this last section (from the western wall – loc 225, 350, east to the dead end – loc 225, 125) clear of adds to have a more enjoyable Black Reaver stomping experience. If you’re not at full strength, wait before clearing that last section. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Targeting: </span>
<br />
 Here’s the deal. There are Black Reavers in two areas. One, of course, is the one we want and he is way up there on that platform. But… there are a bunch of Reavers in the castle as well. You need to position yourself so that the Reaver closest to you is the one way up there on the platform. I tried several methods, but I usually ended up targeting a Reaver in the Castle. The method I found that worked best was to move back around the corridor to a spot along the northernmost edge of the zone and due north of the island. That’s roughly just before the corridor opens up into the courtyard (the courtyard north of #2 on the map). With your pet at that spot (loc 250, 200), use the command “/pet attack a black reaver”. Your pet should respond, “Attacking a Black Reaver, Master”. Now you can target your pet and /assist it to target the Reaver yourself. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Pulling: </span>
<br />
Having acquired your target, go back around the corridor until it faces east and stop just before the steps. Make sure all of your pet buffs are fresh. Casting Valiant Companion is probably not a bad idea. I’m not sure if it helps, but the Reavers can sometimes cause your pet to run off in some random direction. With that in mind, having Summon Companion is also a good idea to keep handy (especially if you have it on an item). 
<br />

<br />
Now you’re ready to see if you have the correct target. First make sure the critical area from the west wall to the dead end at the east is clear. Having done that, make sure that you are facing due east. This is important! Facing east (make sure your pet is behind you) look up at the platform and cast your low-level bolt. If you have spell effects on, you should see the bolt travel up toward the platform. You should also get a message for some damage done to a Black Reaver. If you don’t get the message, you’ve probably targeted the wrong Reaver. If that is the case, you might see your bolt take a right turn into the wall (don’t worry, you won’t hit or pull the Reavers in the castle). If you have the wrong Reaver, go back at different points along the north zone wall and go through the “/pet attack a black reaver” thing. Don’t forget to retarget from your pet. Eventually you will get the correct target and soon the fun will begin. If you don’t, it might be that Neh`Ashir is already up, in that case try targeting Neh`Ashir (note the correct accent mark). 
<br />

<br />
Once you get the damage message, make sure you are still facing due east (and unmounted) and (as described by Taikun) begin to walk slowly forward. What you are now doing is moving into the Reaver’s agro range so that he will warp down in front of you. This usually happened for me where the bridge joins the corridor from the right. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Attack: </span>
<br />
OK, now that you have a huge hunk of black fury in you face, what do you do? Don’t turn; keep facing east! Your pet should still have that “/pet attack a black reaver” command fresh in it’s mind and it will begin to attack. You’ve used a low-level bolt, so the pet should have no trouble in getting agro from you. All you need to do is back up, westward. This is why it’s important to face due east: Black Reavers can blind you. If you are blind there are several things that can happen and they are almost all bad. If you were facing due east, however, all you have to do is keep backing up until you don’t hear the sound of the Reaver beating on you. Since you were facing due east, and you cleared the corridor to the west wall, you can safely back up all the way to that wall while blind. Your pet will have had plenty of time to pull agro from you. You can even cast a pet heal or two using your hot keys until you can see again. As soon as you can see, get on your mount if you have one (all pure casters should have a mount). 
<br />

<br />
Once I had pulled the Reaver, I cast Mala and I tried one or two Malosinias. The latter may not be worth the effort since they are usually resisted and you may need all of the mana you can get if you get a long chain of Reavers. 
<br />

<br />
Stay back away from the Reaver during the fight. Heal your pet, and nuke judiciously. Once you’ve killed the Reaver, another one will spawn right on the spot where the previous one died. If you’re not close to the new Reaver, he will be out of agro range. This will give you time to regroup before tackling the next Reaver (and maybe cast Summon Companion). These follow-up spawns should pose less of a problem since you should have no trouble in making sure that your pet holds agro. Continue in the same manner for each Reaver and soon, instead of a Black Reaver spawn, Neh`Ashir will appear. He (I had a male spawn, but it’s sometimes a she) was not KoS to me (dubious I think), so I took a bit of time to regen some mana and make sure old Jabbober was healthy and fully buffed. I also memmed Annul Magic at this time. The only problem here is that if you wait too long, you might begin to get repops of the trash you cleared. Probably not a big threat but you don’t need distractions while tackling Neh`Ashir. 
<br />

<br />
I hear that Neh`Ashir will wait patiently while you re-clear the area, but I didn’t wait that long. I had a chain of four or five Reavers before Neh`Ashir popped and I waited until I was at 50% mana before I tackled him. If I were to do it again, I would wait for more mana. I put the pet in and immediately cast annul twice. I then used Mala and Malosinia (he seemed to have normal MR) and proceeded to heal the pet and nuke. I was at about 10% mana when Neh`Ashir dropped and my pet was at about 10% health. Not much of a safety margin and Neh`Ashir hadn’t cast a complete heal. That could have meant failure. 
<br />

<br />
I got my torch on the first kill, but if you don’t get yours, you’ll have to wait two hours for the correct Reaver to re-spawn. More fun and more chances to get a Jade Reaver (I didn’t get one). Have fun, and thanks to everyone who contributed to this (i.e. who’s ideas I stole  ) 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">Xtal Matrix</span>
<br />
Arch Convoker
<br />
Brell Serilis</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
